   print header logo
   https://www.chron.com/news/science-environment/article/A-quiet-Wednesda
   y-was-expected-for-Houston-as-14452733.php

Ferocity of Thursday storms surprised many who 'let their guard down'

   By Alex Stuckey
   Updated 4:45 pm CDT, Thursday, September 19, 2019
     *
     *

     *
     *
     *
     *
     *
     *

     * A kid rides his bike near Kings Manor Drive as rain from Tropical
       Depression Imelda inundate the area, Thursday, Sept. 19, 2019, in
       Kingwood. Photo: Jason Fochtman/Staff Photographer
       A kid rides his bike near Kings Manor Drive as rain from Tropical
       Depression Imelda inundate the area, Thursday, Sept. 19, 2019, in
       Kingwood.
       A kid rides his bike near Kings Manor Drive as rain from Tropical
       Depression Imelda inundate the area, Thursday, Sept. 19, 2019, in
       Kingwood.
       Photo: Jason Fochtman/Staff Photographer

     * photo

     *
     *
     *
     *
     *
     *

   Photo: Jason Fochtman/Staff Photographer
   Image 1 of / 4

   Caption

   Close
   Image 1 of 4

   A kid rides his bike near Kings Manor Drive as rain from Tropical
   Depression Imelda inundate the area, Thursday, Sept. 19, 2019, in
   Kingwood.

   A kid rides his bike near Kings Manor Drive as rain from Tropical
   Depression Imelda inundate the area, Thursday, Sept. 19, 2019, in
   Kingwood.
   Photo: Jason Fochtman/Staff Photographer
   Ferocity of Thursday storms surprised many who 'let their guard down'
   1  /  4
   Back to Gallery

   After Wednesday brought only moderate rainfall to most parts of the
   greater Houston area, many residents breathed a sigh of relief,
   thinking they had dodged the worst of Imelda.

   Thursday proved them wrong. Widespread, intense rainfall led to
   high-water rescues, flooding of homes and a hospital evacuation.

   But Thursday's flash floods were not entirely unexpected, National
   Weather Service officials said, with warnings lasting until 7 p.m.

   This kind of misconception is common during tropical storms -- it even
   happened during Hurricane Harvey in 2017, said Jeff
   Evans, meteorologist in charge of the service's Houston/Galveston
   office.

   "It wasn't too bad yesterday, so people almost have a tendency to let
   their guard down based on what they're seeing," Evans said Thursday.
   "Perceptions sometimes don't meet the reality of the messaging."

   Wednesday was actually expected to be calm for much of the Houston
   region, according to Space City Weather, though areas in Jefferson and
   Orange counties were were slammed by rainfall.

   On Thursday, however, the region was pummeled with three separate
   weather systems, which prompted the National Weather Service to issue a
   Flash Flood Emergency warning for the entire region, according to Space
   City Weather.

   The storms were expected to move south later Thursday afternoon.

   As of 4 p.m. Thursday, Imelda had brought more than 43 inches of rain
   to Texas, making it the fifth wettest tropical cyclone for the
   contiguous U.S., according to the Weather Channel.

   Harvey holds the record, with more than 51 inches of rain recorded at a
   gauge near Mont Belvieu.

   Imelda started as a tropical storm in the Gulf of Mexico and made
   landfall in Freeport on Tuesday afternoon. But by Tuesday night, it had
   been downgraded to a tropical depression.

   So what's the difference? Essentially, it's wind.

   A tropical storm comes with maximum winds between 39 and 73 mph.  A
   tropical depression, on the other hand, is a low pressure system,
   accompanied by thunderstorms, that has winds below 39 mph.

   Despite the downgrade, the storm created huge amounts of rainfall -- in
   part because it moved so slowly over the area, at about 5 mph,
   according to the National Weather Service.

   Evans said it would hard to say whether the storm was acting as
   expected. Weather modeling is not an exact science, he added, and the
   storms can be unpredictable.

   But Space City Weather said in a post on its website Thursday that
   today was more significant than originally thought.

   "Unfortunately, while we knew heavy rainfall was likely in parts of the
   city today, we did not anticipate an event as significant in scope as
   this for Thursday," they posted.

   The storm is expected to bring more rainfall to eastern Texas through
   Friday, Evans said.

   Alex Stuckey writes about NASA and science for the Houston Chronicle.
   You can reach her at alex.stuckey@chron.com or
   Twitter.com/alexdstuckey.

